{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_weimaraner_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280656203/1908010101/0556.xml":{"full_text":"Reviews of Trade by the Big\nCommercial Agencies.\nTHE STATISTICAL EXHIBITS\nPeriod Eeviewed One of Activity,\nBut Dullness Later.\nTHE OUTLOOK FOR 1908\nRegarded Not Very Optimistic, But\nthe Prospects Are Somewhat\nReassuring.\nNEW IORK, January 1.?Bradstreet's\nreview of the business year says:\n\"Nineteen hundred and seven was a\nyear of extremes?of excessive, apparent\nly Insatiable, demantj^early, but later o*\ndullness unequaled for years. Coincident\nally there were three separate and distinct\ndeclines in prices of securities. Interspers\ned. however, with rallies depriving the\ngeneral downward movement of the year\nof its uniformity, but foreshadowing the\nlater quieting down of trade and in\ndustry.\n\"Accompanying and as a result of the\nlast great break in stock and bond prices\nthere ensued a marked loss of public con\nfidence, suspensions of financial institu\ntions so swelling business failure liabili\nties as to recall the damage of 1893. and I\n?n a> ute money panic, causing a wide-J\nspread suspension of trade and industry,\nthe year closing with a degree of pessi\nmism as to the outlook only to be com\npared to the feeling of optimism ruling\nat its opering.\n\"The year saw and the markets for se\ncurities and commodities reflected many\ndisturbing occurences, besides witnessing\nthe play of forces and influences having\ntheir inception in preceding years. For\n<>ne thing, it became evident that the en\ntire world?financial, commercial and in\ndustrial?was. in 1007, living beyond its\nmeans, and that the boasted large addi\ntions to the world's stock of gold were\nnot s.ifHolent to offset the destructive\neffects of past wasteful wars, the vast\nloss of property growing out of conflagra\ntions in 190*5 and the increased expendi\ntures of all countries, states, municipali\nties and individuals.\nBurdens on Money Supplies.\n\"Speculation in real estate and mining\nsecurities put additional burdens upon\nmoney supplies, already strained by the\nnecessity of providing sufficient of the cir\nculating medium to carry along the unpre\ncedented demand for all kinds of goods\nselling at the highest prices In years.\nIn addition.' the business and financial\nworld was called on to bear eff'cis of past\nshocks to confidence of investoia at home\nand abroad resulting from life insurance\ndisclosures, the revelations that some\nbanking interests were willing to deny\nfinancial accommodation to ordinary mer\ncantile borrowers, in order that unreason\ning speculation might be fostered, and\nproofs that laws had been evaded by\nsome corporations through freight dis\ncriminations.\n\"The railroads were among the first to\nlearn that short-time notes at high rates\nof interest were a. precarious dependence\nfor supplies of liquid capital, and attacks\nupon these corporations by legislatures\nprevented fresh borrowing, even if capi\ntal wa? to be had. which was doubtful.\nGovernment prosecutions of\" corporations\nalso hurt Investment buying of securities,\nand the lack of conservatism displayed\nby the federal authorities at times when\nthe public mind needed reassurance ajid\ncalming were certainly not helpful.\n\"Incidentally some members of the\nbanking community, in the time of acute\nfear, last October, preached sanity and\nagainst the hoarding of money, and then\ndid what they were inveighing against to\nthe detriment of the entire business com\nmunity. As one critic put it. It was not\nso ijiuch scarce money as it was 'soared'\nmonev that caused the damage In the\nautumn of 1007 after,the actual panl#-was\nstayed by a few giants of finance.\nWholesale trade wis large, but retail\ntrnrte was irregular, and crops were\nTmajJ? 1\nTheNrtS^istical IStory of 1907.\nAGRKlSvi^AL, TIKLDS AND VALUES.\nChange\nYields, from\n1907. 1906.\nCorn. biWMnJk J 2.592.320.000 D. 11.4\nWatrr WhcU 4*>9.442.000 D. 17.0\n?h^?r-Pusb?lsJ 224.ft4S.000 D. 7.4\nBeat. bushels 834,087.000 D. 13.7\ntawbela............. 754.443.000 D. 21.7\nP~ifcc'. bushels 15S.317.000 D. 14.5\nti rA husbfIf '11,5*18.000 P. 5.1\nBiienbcat, bwpfr 14.290.000 D. 2.4\nT\"i?t ?is cereal\" 4.180.U23.000 D. 13.8\nKuahelB 25.851,000 I. 1.0\n1'ntaloeA bushels 897.942,000 D. 3.2\nliar. U>:W ?i\"..877.o00 I. 11.0\nT?Kac<-.r torn* ens. 128.000 l. 2.:;\nRice. bualfla 18.738.000 1. 4.9\n_ I2.ft00.ooo D. 11.1\nHiwat^teo* 1.580,000 I. 4.ti\nH?pa. pounds 48,330.000 D. 13.7\nCbangv\nValue,. from\n11R'T 10OtS.\nCi.rn SI.340.448.00') I. 14.9\nWheat..?, 554.437.0O0 I. 13.0\n<>at? 334.5t*.t>00 I. 9.1\nBarter....fta* 102.058.000 I. 37.9\nRTf JbA 23,088.000 I. 17.3\nRuckwheat..W. 9,975,000 I. 14.3\nTotal aix cereals *2.384.582.000 I. 14.4\nKlaiaood 24 713.000 I>. 4.ti\nPotatooa 181.880.noo I. 17.1\nMar 743.507.000 I. 25.5 j\nTobacco 7rt.23t.000 I. Jl-7\nRice 18.081,11O0 I>. .2\nCot too 850,000,000 D. 9.2\nValue all farm products.$7,412.000.000,1. 10.0\nriXANCE AND- lNDUSTKY.\nClianf\nfrom\n1907. 1906\nHank luring# $144.200,000.000 D. 0.0\n>W<-bsndlse\nImports. estimate.... $1,4.'J0.8ft4,0OO I. 8.0 1\nK.xportj. estimated. fl.ftOH. 2*9.000 I. fl.O\nTotal trtde. **t?mat<*d.. $^..1T?7.17:i.<NiO I. 7.0\nRailway earnings. 10 mo 91.503.4H8.000 I. 12.0\n'Ironist Ion. IV^ntxr 1. r..?rf>#.241.r>*t I. 10.0\nRuildinjr e\"H*?nditnres. $5KS.OO(i 000 D. 7.0\nN>w York stork iu?lc*... 197.S31.000 P. 31.0\nN>w York N>od ?sles.. $.*V40..*?9$.i.OO D. 20.0\nPI* Iron output 25.2DO.OOO p. .4\nIron ore shipment? 41.2ft8.7~5 I. 10.0\nAnthrsrifeoal ?hlpmonta 6ft.r>00.000 I. 79.0\nsho* ahlpments. rates.. 4.700.000 p. fl.o\nI,abor striker* 176.\"00 P. 6* 0\nImmlgrtt Ion. totsl 1332,354 I. 8.0\nOutlook for 1908.\n\"The pain of recent wounds is too acute\nto allow very optimistic views being taken\nas to the outlook for 100$. There la. in\nfact, rather a disposition in trade circles\nto look upon the reverse side of the pic\nture. This Is not extraordinary, however,\nbecause it is usual for the average man\nto be bullish at the top and bearish at\nthe bottom. In addition there is the\nknowledge that trade in other countries\nIs quieting down: tliat a presidential elec\ntion ia impending; that readjustments of\nwages and of prices are sure to follow\nstock and money market convulaions, and\nthat expenditures for alt public and pri\nvate purposes are likely to be smaller\nfoe some time to come.\nOn the other iiand. It should not be for\ngotten that there is a large and very\nprofitable business to be done In this\ncountry In supplying the wants of the\n84.tl00.00n people that inhabit it. and that\nthe warnings to the country of the pres\nent trouble were so early and ao numer\nous thai large accumulations of stocks\nand bonds were avoided.\"\nB. O. Sun Co.'a Review.\nThe withdrawal of $125,000,000 from a\nfew large trust companies, precipitating\na season of hoarding and sending cur\nrency to a premium at a time when it\nwaa most needed throughout the country\n'.a credited in R. G. Dun Co.'s annual\nreview of trade, published yesterday,\nwith havipg been one of the great factors\nin turning the year 1W7 from Its prom\n1seof new records In prosperity to a .losing\noeriod of financial disturbance that\nauaed many plans for futurv extensions\nof business to be either abandoned or\npostponed. The restoration of normal\nconditions, the r?view declares, depends\nupon eaaler money and a revival of con\nfidence. both of which seerr nearer today\nthan at any time since October, when the\nstringency began. While failures were\nV\nfrequent during the last quarter of the\nyear. the review points out that if the\ncomparison is carried back to previous\nperiods of distress there is much cause\nfor congratulation in the insolvency re\nturns. The review says In part:\n\"The year 1907 started under auspices\nthat seemed bright beyond precedent, and I\nthe movement of trade attained a velocity\nthat constantly promised new records of\nprosperity. For almost ten months sta\ntistics of production, bank exchanges,\nrailway earnings and other measures of\ncommercial activity compared favorably\nwith any previous year, and in many in\nstances the total for the twelve months\nwas never eclipsed. Products of the farms\nfar surpassed all earlier records, high\nprices more than compensating for small\ner crops of some cereals and cotton than\nIn banner years. Immigration and foreign\ncommerce both exceeded any previous\nyear, gold in the Treasury rose to $9.V),\n000,000. and the amount of money in cir\nculation per capita became greater than\never before, despite a correction in the\ngold estimate of $135,000,000 and an in\ncrease In population to more than 86,600.\n000. Conditions changed radically during\nthe last ten weeks of 1907.\nHeavy Withdrawal of Deposits.\n\"Probably the year might have ended\nwithout any sensationally high quotations\nfor money had it not been for the heavy\nwithdrawals of deposits from a few large\ntrust companies that precipitated a season\nof hoarding. No accurate figures are\navailable regarding the extent of this\nmovement, but it is estimated by well\nposted bankers that the cash withdrawn\nfrom New York banks alone amounted\nto $12.\".000,000. and perhaps four times as\nmuch throughout the country.\n\"Insolvencies were not unusually numer\nous in 19<i7. despite some increase in the\nlast quarter, but as the year advanced\nthere were more defaults of exceptional\nsize, and liabilities in the fourth quarter\nexceeded those of any three-month period\nsince 1S93. Considering the severity of\nthe financial disturbance and the inability\nof the banks to provide mcrcantils ac\ncommodations. it is extremely gratif3*ing\nthat failures were not much more numer\nous. while the comparative lightness of\nthe aggregate amount of defaulted indebt\nedness is the more striking when it is\nrealized how vastly the nation's business\nhas grown.\n\"Changes in the iron and steel industry\nduring 1907 were more striking than else\nwhere. particularly in respect to the vol\nunv of production. During the early part\nof the year there was a gradual increase\nin output, the weekly active capacity of\nblast furnaces constantly establishing new\nrecords until the high point was reached\nJuly 1. with a total of 528.170 tons of pig\niron a week. From this point a moderate\ndecrease occurred, until toward the end of\nthe year it was estimated that not more\nthan about 33 per cent of the entire iron\nand steel capacity was in operation.\nBig Returns for the Farmers.\n\"Although in many cases the size of\ncrops in 1907 fell below some preceding\nyears, high prices made the return to the\nfarmer much larger than ever before.\nAdding the value of cotton, meats, dairy\nproducts. poultry, eggs and all other items\nraised by the agriculturist, the year's\ntotal attains the phenomenal value of\n$7,400,000,000.\n\"Cotton has ruled at a high position\nthroughout the year, while the latest sta\ntistics of the crop indicate a yield of\n12,000.000 bales, or 10 per cent less than\nthe high record established in the previous\nyear.\n\"Conflicting influences united to produce\na year in the dry goods market which\nhas been without precedent for the vol\nume of business done, but which has also\nbeen honeycombed with disappointments\nthat reduce the average of what might\notherwise be regarded as a most success\nful twelve months. Although hides broke\nto lower figures than had been reached\nbefore in about a decade, leather kept\nfairly steady throughous most of the\nyear. The comparative steadiness of\nleather values has been due almost entire\nly to the curtailment of production.\n\"The year has been characterized as\na period of retrenchment Hi the shoe trade,\nand prices have undergone a readjustment\nfrom the top rates that prevailed late in\n1906.\"\nWHOLESALE MARKET REPORT.\nQuotations given below are for large\nlots. Jobbers' prices from 1 cent to\ncents higher.\nEGOS.?Nearby fresh Virginia. 27a28.\nWest Virginia and southwest Virginia.\n26a27; Tennessee, 25a29; North Caro\nlina, 24a25; cold-storage, 19a20.\nBUTTER,?Creamery, fancy. ;t0a.?m.\nWestern, firsts, 20a2fltt; seconds, 24a25.\nProcess, fancy. 2?a27; fair to good. 22a\n23. Store-packed, fresh, 19a20.\nCHEESE.?New York state factory,\nrew, large. lBHal\".\nPOULTRY.?Chickens, spring, per lb\nHalo; hens, per lb., 13; roosters, per\nlb.. 7: keats, per lb., 12; turkeys, toms.\nper lb., 15; hens, per lb., 15. Ducks,\nper lb.. lOall.\nDRESSED POULTRY.?Hens, choice,\nper lb., 13al4; roosters, per lb., 7a8;\nchickens, per lb., 14al6; ducks, per lb..\n13al6; turkeys, hens, per lb.. 17al8;\ntoms, per lb., 16al7.\nVEGETABLES. Potatoes, rer bbl..\nNo. 1. 2.00; per bu., 75a80; No. 2, per\nbbl.. 7Bal.00; sweet potatoes, nor bbl..\n3.00a4.00; yams, per bbl,. 2 00a2.50;\nturnips, per box, 40; per bbl., 1.25;\nrutabagas, per bbl.. 1.25a2.00; cu\ncumbers. per dozen. 50a<10: onions, per\nbbl., 2.00; per bu., R0a85: peppers, Fla.,\nper carrier. 1.00al.75: cabbage, per hun\ndred pounds. 80n83; cauliflower, per\nbbl 3.0Oa4.O0: kale, per bbl., 75al.OO;\nspinach, per bbl., 2.00*2.50; eggplant,\nper crate. 1.50al.75; squash, Fla., per\ncrate. 75al.25; sn?P beans, I'la., per\nbasket. 2.00a3.o0; new beets, oer bunch.\n4a6; lettuce. Fla., per basket, 50al.25;\nokra. per carrier. 3.00; celsry. per\nbunch, 40a65: Brussels sprouts, per qt.,\n10al5; tomatoes. Fla.. per crate. 2.50a\n8.50; parsley. New Orleans, per bunch, 5.\nGREEN FRUITS.?Apples, per bbl\n2.50a5.00: oranges, Fla.. per bos. 2.00a\n3.50; grape fruit, per crate, 3-00*4-50;\ntangerines, per strap. 3.00a5.00; Sat\nsumas. per strap. 2.00a3.00; pineapples,\nFla.. per crate, Ji.00a4.00; pears, Kelfer,\nrer bbl.. 4,OOa5.m>; cranberries, per box,\n,50a2.50; per bbl., 7.00a9.00.\nHAY AND STRAW.?Hay. western,\nNo. 1. 18.50a19.50; No. 2, 17.50al8.00;\nmixed. 16.00al7.00. Straw, rye, bundle,\n14.50al5.00; rye, machine-thrash, 9.00a\n9.50; wheat, 6.50a7.00; oat straw, per\nton. 9.00a9.50.\nDRESSED MEAT.?Pork. small nnd\nneat^per cwt., 6.50a7.00; large. 5.50a6.00.\nLIVE STOCK.?Cattle, extra, per\ncwt.. 5.00; butcher, per cwt., 4.<>Oa4.50;\nordinary, per cwt.. 2.50a3.00. Hogs, per\ncwt., gross. 5.00a5.25. Sheep, per lb.. 3a4;\nlambs, choice, 6Vja7. Calves, choice, per\nlb., 9a9Vi: medium, per lb., 8H. Cows,\nprime, fresh, each, 4u.00a50.00; common\neach, 20.00a30.00.\nBEEF CUTS.?Ribs. No. 1. per lb., 15;\nNo. 2. 12; No. 3. 10. Rounds, No. 1, per\nlb- 10; No. 2, 9; No. 3. 7. Loins, No. 1.\nper lb.. 14; No. 2, 12; No. 3. 10. Chucks,\nNo. 1, per lb.. 8H; No. 2, 7; No. 3, ti.\nWOOL AND HIDES.?Wool washed,\nfree of burrs, per lb? 25; unwashed. 18a\n21. Hides, green, per lb., 5; green salt\ned. 6; dry. Ball. Sheepskins, green,\neach, 50a75; dry, 25a(S0. Mink, each,\n3.00a4.00; raccoon. 25a90; red fox, 1.25a\n1.75; skunk, 25al.OO; opossum, 10a20;\ngray fox, 35a60; muskrat, 12a20; musk\nrat kits, 5; rabbit skins. 1. Calfskins,\ngreen, each, 1.0oal.'.'5; dry flint hides,\nper lb., 9; dry salted hides, 8.\nGRAIN.?Wheat, 88al.OO. Corn, shell\ned, old, white. U9a71; yellow, 7E; new\n59a62; new, ear, 3.0<>a3.25. Oats, west\nern. white. No. 2. 55a57; mixed, 53a55.\nBran, per ton, 28.00a30.00. Middlings,\nper ion, 28.00a30.00.\nFour Suits Against B. and 0. Road.\nBALTIMORE, January 1.?Four suits\n(or an aggregate of $61,000 damages were\ninstituted against the Baltimore and Ohio\nRailroad Company In the superior court\nyesterday as the result of the collision,on\nthe road December 3 at Hanover station.\nAnne Arundel county. Two of the suits\nwere brought by Carroll C. Fogarty and\nEllen Frances Fogarty. children, who\nclaim, respectively. $20,000 and $10,000\nj damage. for injuries received in the ac\ncident. Their father. Patrick T. Fo\ngarty. claims $1,000 damages in a sepa\nrate suit for expenses Incurred by him\nbecause of the Injuries to his children.\nIn tlw fourth suit Katlierine Colein claims\n$30.0o0 damages for injuries she received\nin the accident\nTHE PHILADELPHIA HINT.\nTotal Output for the Year Just\nClosed.\nPHILADELPHIA, January 1.?The to\ntal output at the United States mint in\nthis city for the year 1007. according-to\nreports compiled yesterday, was 183,\n598,043 coins, rspresenting a value of $63,\n263,104.93.\nFor the year of 1906 the output was\n166.653.233, therefore there Is an in\ncrease in this year's production over last\nyear s of 16,048,710 pieces.\nDuring the past year there were 4,230,\n800 gold pieces coined, representing a\nvalue of $54,001,400. The total coinage of\nsilver wan 32,011,725. of a value of $5.\n310.4X8. and in base coins?pennies and\nnickels?the production was 147,353.418,\ndenoting a value of *3.042.126.18. Of the\nnew design of eagles and double-eagles,\nwith high relief and modified, #12.073\npieces were coined, representing a value\nof $0,840,000.\nFor the Philippine government the fol\nlowing number of coins were struck off:\nFifty centaros. 1,200.625. value $203,\n0.^; twenty centaros, 1,20,651, value,\n$84,618; ten centaros, 1,500,781. value. $50,\ntotal, 3,052.075; total value, 1338.473.\nFor the Panama government these\ncoins were made: 1-40 balboas, 800.000,\nvalue In United States money, $40,000; I\n1-200 balboas. 1.000,000. value. $25,000;\ntotal. 1,800.000; total value. $65,000.\nBALTIMORE CUSTOMS RECEIPTS\nCollector Stone's Report Shows\nLarge Growth of Business.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE, Md., January 1.?Collec\ntor Stone's report of the business of the\nport of Baltimore In 1007 Is gratifying in\nthat it shows the enormous business\ntransacted through the local custom\nhouse, and that this business is Increas\ning constantly.\nThe total value of imports for 1907 was\n$36,070,707. Of these Imports $20,286,462\nworth were dutiable, and the rest, valued\nat $15,784,245, were free. The total re\nceipts were $5,414,005.40, an increase over\nUK>6 of $174,009.07.\nFor 1807 the Imports amounted to $5.\n083,654 dutiable. $ii,042.003 free, making a\ntotal of $11,126,557, and in 1807 the total\ncollections summed up $2.2S7.111.10. To\ncollect this amount in 1807 It cost the\nUnited States government $254,362.00, and\nthere were employed In the customs serv\nice at that time 192 persons. To collect\nthe greatly increased amount for 1907.\nwhich shows an Increase In imports over\n1807 of $24,944,150, and of the amount col\nlected an increase of $3,127,794.30, the\nUnited States government expended $284,\n055.80, and there were employed 210 per\nsons.\nThe figures representing the imports of\n1907 do not either directly or indirectly\nindicate the large amount as represented\nin values of goods received at this port\nand transported to Interior and other\nports for distribution and consumption\nthere. For instance, It is estimated that\nfor the year 1907 the customs service at\nBaltimore handled for Interior ports be\ntween $3,000,000 and $4,000,000, and that\nif those goods had been entered at this\nport and the duty paid here on them our\nreceipts would have been Increased at\nleast $2,000,000. which would show a tre\nmendous increase over the figures which,\neven In themselves, are most gratifying.\nThe exports for 1007 show an approxi\nmate aggregate of $90,543,701. which shows\na decrease as compared with 1006 of $8.\n065.383, which is, of course, to be' re\ngretted. But ng compared with the ex\nports of 1S97 the exports for the last year\nshow an increase of about $2,000,000.\nwhich is pleasing and gratifying.\nROYALTY IN BUSINESS.\nCarmen Sylva's Book Stores?Queen\nof Portugal's Chemist Shop.\nFrom Tit-Bits.\nIt is populaj-ly supposed that all Indus\ntrial \"kings' come from America, but\nEurope can still boast a few records, and\namong them Is the production of real,\ngenuine business monarchs. For Instance,\nthe kaiser is the proprietor of a most\nimportant porcelain factory at Cadlnen,\nand, as might be expected, he does not\ndelegate the duties to others.\nBut the kaiser is only one of many\nmonarchs who have gone into trade. King\nPeter of Servia is perhaps the most un\nconventional of them all, for he runs a\nbarber shop, owns a patent medicine and\nconducts a motor car agency in his cap\nital.\nThe reigning Prince of Llppe-Detmold\ndeals in butter and eggs, while a pros\nperous brick factory swells his profits.\nThe King of Wurtemburg is the pro\nprietor of two hotels in his kingdom,\nand they add ?10,000 a year to his majes\nty's revenue.\nThe Emperor of Austria owns a china\nware factory in Vienna which Is one of\nthe most famous in the world, and em\nploys over 1,000 skilled workmen. The\nKing of Saxony conducts a similar busi\nness. though on a much smaller scale;\nbut, according to report, trade is increas\ning. so his majesty need not keep\n\"awake o' nights\" wondering if his trav\nelers are fit for their jobs.\nQueen Carmen Sylva Is the only work\ning journalist among the crowned heads\nof Europe, but her tnajesty lias within\nlate years added a bookseller's shop to\nthe affairs of her state. This may be seen\nin Bucharest, and is the leading house\nin the trade. Lately she lias opened a\nbookshop in Paris.\nThe Queen of Portugal has a chemist's\nshop in Lisbon, registered In her own\nname. Unlike the various other busi\nnesses enumerated in this article, the\nLisbon establishment is conducted solely\nin the interests of charity, and conse\nquently when the queen attends to the\ngrants of her customers personally?she\noften makes up prescriptions herself?\nshe is working in a good cause and need\nfear no criticism.\nWild Turkey Drive.\nFrom the St. Louitt'ilobe-Doraorrat.\nDeer drives and wolf hunts may be in\nteresting, but I think the turkey drive we\ntook part In ud in the Ozarks recently\nhas them all beaten for real sport. The\nhunters of our party had assembled long\nbefore daylight. The night before one set\nof men had been sent into Maries county,\nten miles away. Others were sent five\nmiles to the right and left, and our com\npany was to complete the circle, the vari\nous parties converging at a point agreed\nupon.\nRifles were not allowed, all carrying\nshotguns. The country was alive with\ngame?rabbits, auail and soulrrel; but our\nattention was not to be diverted.\nOur parLy had scarcely started when a\nsingle gobbler was seen, while the fresh\nsnow was well marked with tracks. There\nis no warier bird than the turkey, and few\nharder to kill. Unlike the deer, he is not\ninauisitlve and as soon as danger Is\nscented scoots for safety.\nAbout noon the circle began to narrow\nand shots were heard from the other par\nties. We were hidden in a dense tangle\nof underbrush when the fun began. Budd\nBruer shot and crippled a hep. while Ed\nReynolds was iust In time to land on a\nfine big gobbler. These shots scattered\nthe bunch, and four i-ame straight for our\nhiding place. There were more than,\nthirty turkeys in the little valley at one\ntime, and we got seven of them.\nBaltimore Clearings Increase.\nBALTIMORE. January 1.?The yearly\nclearings of the Baltimore banks for\n1907 ran nearly $29,000,000-a head of those\nfor the previous year. In 1906 the total\nwas $1,444,859,075, while for the year just\nclosed they aggregated $1,472,011,207. The\nclearings fell off materially In the last\nfour months of the year, those for De\ncember being only $104,208,595, the small\neat total for a similar period in some\nyears. The decline was due to the falling\noff in business, to tlie scarcity of money\nand to the small use of checks during the\neloping months.\nThe English Workman.\nFrom tbe English Nation.\nNext to this \"sentimentality.\" so aston\nishing to Europe?because so irrational\ncomes the invincible patience of the Eng\nlish workman. He will endure almost\nanything?In silence?until it becomes un\nendurable. When he is vocal it is pretty\ncertain that things have become unen\ndurable\nCOLTON FUNDS MISSING.\nSafety Deposit Box Opened at New\nYork and Found Empty.\nNEW TORK. January 1.?Upon a court\norder, a safe deposit box in the* vaults of\nthe Atlantic Safe Deposit Company was\nopened yesterday in furtherance of a\nsearch for securities missing from the es\ntate of the late Mrs. Ellen M. Colton of\nWashington, D. C. The box proved to be\nempty.\nThe original custodians of the securities\nwere Walter J. Bartnett, president of the\nCalifornia Surety and Trust Company of\nSan Francisco, now closed, and J. Daliell\nBrown, vice president of the same institu\ntion. Both Bartnett and Brown are now\nunder grand jury Indictments. Following\ntheir arrests, a search for the securities\nwas Instituted. Some were subsequently\nrecovered from the vault of the company\nof which they were officers. Brown. It is\nsaid, told a California bank examiner that\nthe securities were in the local banking\nhouse. The total value of the missing pa\npers was $400,000.\nPending the possible location of the\nbonds and stocks, the local courts will be\nthe next theater of operations in the re\nmarkable will contest, because the effort\nto prove whether the District of Columbia\nor California was the domicile f Mrs. El\nlen M. Colton will be tried before Justice\nBarnard this month. Also of interest in the\ndetermination of the distribution of Mrs.\nColton's wealth, estimated at about $1,000.\n000, is the trial of Walter J. Bartnett. the\nexecutor named by the testatrix, who was\nrecently arrested on a charge of embez\nzlement growing out of the failure of\nthe California Deposit and Trust Com\npany. Mr. Bartnett was custodian of the\nnow missing securities, and the safe de\nposit box opened at the Atlantic Safe De\nposit Company, New York, yesterday be\nlonged to the California financial institu\ntion. The order for its opening was se\ncured from the New York courts on the\nstrength of information that the Colton\nstocks and bonds were part of the papers\ndeposited in New York by the California\nDeposit and Trust Company. It was\nthought fully half of Mrs. Colton's wealth\nwould be found, and great was the disap- j\npointment when the opening of the box\ndisclosed only empty space and dust.\nWashingtonians present at the Atlan\ntic Safe Deposit Company's vaults yes- j\nterday included:\nAttorneys Charles A. Douglas, Brain\nard Parker, collectors appointed by the\nDistrict Probate Court, and R. Golden\nDonaldson, representing little Helen\nSacher of Paris, contesting the will.\nAttorney Conrad H. S.vme, counsel for\nMrs. Catharine Martin Dahlgren, daugh\nter of Mrs. Colton, and chief beneficiary\nunder the will, did not go to New York,\nand he said today that he felt that the\ninterests of his client, in the simple mat\nter of the opening of the safe deposit\nbox, would be fully conserved by the col\nlectors appointed by the local Probate\nCourt. Speaking of the next steps to\nward the recovery of the securities. Mr.\nSyme said: \"We have notified all the\ncompanies whose bonds and stocks were\nin the list of Mrs. Colton's possessions,\ntelling them to make no transfers on\ntheir books. Through these stock and\nbond books, too, every effort will be\nmade to trace the missing securities, if\nany of them have found their way into\nthe market.\"\nTHE IRON INDUSTRY.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nCLEVELAND, Ohio. January l.-The\nIron Trade Review tomorrow will say:\nA series of conferences of tin plate manu\nfacturers participated in by the leading\ninterests and independents have been held\nwltoin a few days to devise means of\nmaintaining prices throughout the first\nI quarter of the year. Pig iron and other\ninterests are also conferring. While\nnothing definite has yet been announced,\nit is believed that a better understand\ning of conditions and of policies necessary\nto hasten a return of prosperity will be\nobtained.\nAlthough developments at the close of\nthe old year were not as positive as might\nhave been hoped for, there were enough\nfavorable indications to Justify a cheerful\nfeeling.\nContinued increase of interest In the\npig Iron market is reported, and some\ni sales are being made. In the Chicago and\nCincinnati markets there is a firmer tone,\nwith some promise of fair orders, al\nthough heavy buying is not expected.\nSouthern furnace men are acting with\nmore harmony than for some time. Oc\ncasionally a selling Interest manifests a\ndisposition to be aggressive and to ob\ntain business at concessions, but as a\nrule prices are being well maintained. A\nfew more stacks have been blown out.\nand others are expected to be added to\nthe idle list this week. The outlook is\nthat the price of Bessemer pig iron for\nthe first quarter will be about $19 valley.\nAfter being married a week without any\none at home knowing it. Edward M. De\nhaven. a teacher of Clarke county and\npostmaster at Dehaven. Va., has returned\nto Winchester with Ws bride, who was\nMiss Flora Virginia Hull\nFINANCIAL.\nFOR SAIjEJ?1 OR 2 7% $300 TEN\nyear gold bonds of an established\nNew York company, secured by\nreal estate in New York valued at\nmore than twice the Indebtedness.\nFull particulars on application.\nC. A., care of The Star. Jal-3t\nWe Wish You a\nHappy NewYear\nMay it bring you much\nhappiness, and may your\nbank account steadily in\ncrease.\nHome Savings Bank\n\"tli and Mass. Ave. N.W.\nBRANCHES:\n7th and H Sts. N.E.\n436 7th St. S.W.\nUnder Supervision of the\nU. S. Treasury.\n\"WHAT HAS\nHE DONE?\"\n?Napoleon's Famous Question.\nNapoleon Bonaparte arose from a nobody to\nconsiderably more than a somebody. lie need\nHOOD MEN?men of brains, bravery and action.\nHe determined their abilities by their records\nhence his Invariable. Inevitable and famous\nquestion. \"What has lie done'/'\" Ask this ques\ntiun Iierslatently?It's a Rood vv*y to judge men.\nMy record as a twenty-one rears builder here in\nWashington Is an open book.\nARTHUR COWSILL,\n\"The Builder Who Makes Good,-'\n311 COLORADO BLDG., 14TH AND G 8TS.\n\nCAPITAL, $1,000.000?SURPLUS. ?1.400.000.\n^fj\" ETTERS OF\nCREDIT Issued.\nDrafts issued direct 